AB  - The text explores the relationship between total factor productivity (TFP) change, output growth and variables related to trade orientation. The results for the Brazilian manufacturing industries indicate that TFP change is positively associated with output growth, the relationship being stronger for the slow-growth period 1980–1985 than for the high-growth quinquennium 1975–1980. In the former period TFP change accounts for nearly all of output change. A multisectoral demand-side decomposition model highlights the role of trade-related variables in accounting for a sizeable proportion of output change. An additional preliminary result is the finding of positive impacts of trade orientation on the pattern of TFP change across industries.
